"""Overlay BUILD file applied to every `wgpu_native_<os>_<arch>` http_archive.

Each archive unzips to:

    include/webgpu/webgpu.h        -- standard WebGPU C header
    include/webgpu/wgpu.h          -- wgpu-native extensions
    lib/libwgpu_native.so          -- dynamic library (Linux)        [linux archives only]
    lib/libwgpu_native.dylib       -- dynamic library (macOS)        [macos archives only]
    lib/libwgpu_native.a           -- static library (unused; dylib is smaller)
    wgpu-native-meta/webgpu.yml    -- API schema (unused at runtime)

Exposes the shared library + C headers as a single `wgpu_native` cc_library.
The same overlay file is applied to every per-platform archive, but each
archive contains only its own shared library — `.so` on Linux, `.dylib` on
macOS. Using `glob(..., allow_empty = True)` makes the overlay a no-op on
the three wrong archives and a functional `srcs = [...]` on the right one.

`//third_party/webgpu-cpp:wgpu_native_platform` then picks the archive
matching the current host via `select()`, so only the matching archive's
`:wgpu_native` target ever ends up in the runtime link line.
"""

package(default_visibility = ["//visibility:public"])

cc_library(
    name = "wgpu_native",
    hdrs = [
        "include/webgpu/webgpu.h",
        "include/webgpu/wgpu.h",
    ],
    includes = ["include"],
    # allow_empty keeps this cc_library analyzable even inside the three
    # "wrong" platform archives that don't contain a matching shared lib.
    # The //third_party/webgpu-cpp:wgpu_native_platform alias only ever
    # routes the host-matching archive into a real link step.
    srcs = glob(
        [
            "lib/libwgpu_native.so",
            "lib/libwgpu_native.dylib",
        ],
        allow_empty = True,
    ),
    # wgpu-native's dynamic library already contains everything it needs (no
    # external deps), so no linkopts are required on the consumer side beyond
    # linking the library itself. On macOS Bazel's darwin toolchain handles
    # the framework dependencies (Metal, QuartzCore, etc.) because they're
    # baked into libwgpu_native.dylib's LC_LINKER_OPTIONs; on Linux glibc +
    # pthread + dl are the only external dependencies and the linker picks
    # them up automatically through the `linkstatic=0` default.
)
